title: Right-wing anti-immigrant party poised to win Vienna vote
text:
Campaigning on Austrian fears of mass migration, right wing party poised to Vienna elections 
THE ASSOCIATED PRESS Published: 10/11/15 10:46 am EDT - Updated: 10/11/15 10:46 am EDT 
VIENNA â€” A right-wing populist Austrian party that critics say exploits fears about mass migration was poised Sunday to win control of Vienna. 
A win of Sunday's election for Vienna's municipal government by the Freedom Party would end Socialist dominance of the Austrian capital since World War II. It would also position party leader Heinz-Christian Strache to bid for Austria's chancellorship in federal elections to be held within three years. 
Polls had shown the Socialists ahead by only a few percentage points before the vote, with concerns about immigration a major issue for voters. 
Belying the significance of the election, both top candidates exuded calm as they cast their ballots. 
Incumbent Michael Haeupl said he had an "excellent" night's sleep. Asked about the importance of Sunday's elections, he replied "every election is important." 
Alluding to the Freedom Party's Eurosceptic, anti-immigrant image among its critics, he said that every vote for the party "is not good for the international reputation of this city." 
Strache expressed hope for his party's "best showing in history," saying he hoped to at least match the Socialist showing. 
Voting stations opened at 0500 GMT (1 a.m. EDT) and were to close at 1500 GMT (11 a.m. EDT) Sunday. Full results were expected by late evening. Top candidate for the local elections in Vienna Heinz Christian Strache from the right-wing Freedom Party, FPOE, casts his vote at a polling station in Vienna, Austria, Sunday, Oct. 11, 2015. (AP Photo/Ronald Zak)
